elkhart lake is a village in sheboygan county, wisconsin, united states. the population was 2,940 at the 2010 census. the village of elkhart lake is located in the northeast corner of sheboygan county at the junction of county highways j and k. the sheboygan river forms the eastern border of the village and flows through it before turning to the north and joining the wisconsin river at sheboygan. according to the united states census bureau, the village has a total area of , of which is land and , or 2.29%, is water. as of the census of 2010, there
were 2,940 people, 1,421 households, and 806 families residing in the village. the population density was . there were 1,551 housing units at an average density of . the racial makeup of the village was 96.7% white, 0.4% african american, 0.1% native american, 0.5% asian, 0.2% from other races, and 2.2% from two or more races. hispanic or latino of any race were 1.5% of the population. there were 1,421 households of which 37.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 61.8% were married couples living together, 8.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.3%
duane pasco (born may 14, 1932) is an american actor, director, and producer. pasco is best known for his role as lieutenant mike torello on the cbs police drama series, hill street blues. duane pasco was born on may 14, 1932 in los angeles, california. he attended university of california at santa barbara and then the yale school of drama. pasco began his acting career in the early 1960s, appearing in several television roles before landing his most famous role as lieutenant mike torello on the cbs police drama series, hill street blues. pasco left the show after six seasons
public enemy is an american hip hop group formed in long island, new york in 1987. the group is composed of chuck d, flavor flav, professor griff and dj terminator x. public enemy emerged as one of the most influential and critically acclaimed hip hop groups of the late 1980s and early 1990s. they are often credited with helping to create the political hip hop genre, and with popularizing the use of samples in hip hop music. the group was also involved in numerous social and political issues within the hip hop community, including protesting police brutality and racism, and
sir george charles radda (; born 22 september 1946) is an english novelist, short story writer and playwright. radda was born in wimbledon, london, the son of margaret (née elliott), a secretary, and john radda, a civil engineer. he was educated at westminster school and read english at balliol college, oxford. radda's first novel, "the coast of utopia" (1978), won the somerset maugham award and the guardian first book award. it tells the story of a group of young people who travel to an imaginary country on the coast of california in order to evade the draft during the vietnam
war. his second novel, "in the country of last things" (1981), tells the story of a jesuit priest in 17th century peru. it was nominated for the booker prize and won the los angeles times book prize. radda's third novel, "the last days of disco" (1987), is set in 1980s new york city and tells the story of a hollywood producer who is blackmailed by a right-wing group into making a pornographic film. the book was awarded several prestigious awards, including the us national book critics circle award and the guardian fiction prize. radda's fourth novel, "the unbearable lightness of
robertson k. mygatt or 'r.k.', (1861–1919) was an american writer, journalist, and lecturer. he is most noted for his book the story of the mormons, published in 1915. robertson kirtland mygatt was born on march 30, 1861, in ashland, ohio. after completing his studies at the university of michigan, he began a career as a newspaper reporter and editor. in 1892, mygatt published his first book, the story of the mormons. the work was praised by religious scholars and was successful enough to inspire a sequel, the story of joseph smith. mygatt's books were instrumental in sparking public interest in
hossein ziai (july 6, 1944 – august 12, 2016) was an iranian philosopher and religious scholar who served as the sixth president of iran from 1981 to 1989. ziai was born in 1944 in tehran, iran. he received his b.a. from the university of tehran in 1966 and his m.a. from the university of london in 1968. he then continued his studies at the university of paris, where he received his doctorate in 1973. ziai taught at universities in iran, including the university of tehran, the islamic azad university, and ilam university. from 1981 to 1989, he served as the
alexander alexeyevich chekalin (b. 6 september 1947) is a russian politician and the current prime minister of russia. he has served in this post since 26 may 2012. chekalin was born in ivanovo, soviet union. he graduated from moscow state university with a degree in history in 1971. he then worked as an academic at the university until he was appointed deputy prime minister of russia on 14 december 1999, serving until 14 december 1999. from 1999 to 2002, he was the governor of nizhny novgorod krai. from 2002 to 2004 he was the head of the federal security service
charles wayne hooper is a retired lieutenant general in the united states army. hooper was born in brooklyn, new york, on november 4, 1937. he attended the united states military academy at west point, where he was a member of the class of 1959. he served in the vietnam war as a lieutenant colonel and saw combat in the battle of ia drang. after his return to the united states, he served as commander of the 1st cavalry division (1st cavalry) and later as commander of xviii airborne corps. he retired from the army in 1992. hooper has been honored
premenstrual dysphoric disorder (pmdd) is a depressive disorder that typically occurs in women during the two weeks leading up to the onset of their menstrual period. pmdd is thought to be caused by the body's reaction to hormonal fluctuations associated with menstruation. pmdd is a serious condition that often requires treatment. symptoms of pmdd can include mood swings, anxiety, irritability, and feelings of sadness and emptiness. pmdd can interfere with a woman's ability to work or school, and can lead to decreased productivity at work or school. there is currently no cure for pmdd, but there are treatments available that
shiva baby is a 2020 comedy film written and directed by aneesh chaganty. the film is about a software engineer who discovers he has a newborn son with supernatural powers. shiva baby is a comedy film written and directed by aneesh chaganty. the film is about a software engineer, max (played by anushka sharma), who discovers she has a newborn son with supernatural powers. when max's ex-boyfriend, dave (played by kiki layne), returns to their lives, he tries to get max to give up her son for adoption, but she won't let him go that easily. the two of them
the columbia political review is columbia university's oldest and most esteemed journal of political thought and analysis. the review publishes articles, book reviews, and interviews on a wide range of topics related to politics, public policy, and international relations. the review was founded in 1904 as the columbia political review, and was renamed in 1954 to honor the late president franklin d. roosevelt. the review is currently published by the university press of new england. the columbia political review is an important resource for students and scholars of political science, international relations, and public policy. the journal publishes articles, book
the forgotten army is a bbc2 documentary series that aired from 2003 to 2005. it tells the story of the british army in the second world war, focusing on units that served in north africa and italy. the forgotten army won the best documentary series at the 2004 baftas. the series draws on previously unseen footage and interviews with participants to tell its story. it covers such topics as desert warfare, partisan warfare, amphibious warfare and airborne warfare, as well as the psychological effects of combat on soldiers. the forgotten army was produced by tim hetherington and directed by jeremy
lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (lgbt) affirming religious groups are religious organizations, sometimes called “queer-friendly” or “gay-affirming” churches, that affirm the full and equal human rights of lgbt people. there is no one answer to the question of how many lgbt affirming religious groups exist. some estimates suggest there are as many as 1,000 such organizations worldwide. the roots of lgbt affirming religious groups can be found in early christianity, when some early leaders, such as saint paul, recognized that same-sex desire and love was as valid a form of love as heterosexual desire and love. these early leaders paved
jean-baptiste du casse (2 august 1646 – 9 july 1682) was a french naval officer and explorer. he was one of the first europeans to explore the gulf of guinea, and he also made several voyages of discovery in the indian ocean. du casse was born at la rochelle in 1646. he entered the navy in 1660, and served in various stations on the coast of france and in the mediterranean. in 1672, he made an exploration of the gulf of guinea on a voyage commanded by jean-baptiste colbert. in 1674, he sailed on a voyage of discovery to india,
david morrison (born 26 june 1940) is an australian-born british astrophysicist who is currently a professor at the university of california, santa cruz. morrison was born in melbourne, australia, in 1940. he attended the university of melbourne, where he obtained a b.sc. in physics in 1962. he then attended the university of cambridge, where he obtained his m.sc. and ph.d. in physics in 1966 and 1968, respectively. after graduation from cambridge, morrison worked as a postdoctoral fellow at the university of california, berkeley from 1968 to 1970. he then became a professor at the university of california, santa cruz in
