angaleena loletta mccoy presley (born september 1, 1966) is an american singer, songwriter, actress, author, and businesswoman. she was born in memphis, tennessee, the daughter of elvis presley's first wife priscilla and his father vernon presley. presley has released five studio albums and two compilation albums. her debut album, "heartbreak hotel" (1992), produced four top 10 singles on the billboard hot 100, including "are you lonesome tonight?" which became her first number one single in the united states. her second album, "elvis" (1996), also produced four top 10 singles on the billboard hot 100 and won her a grammy award
for best female pop vocal performance. presley's third album, "in the zone" (2001), produced three top 10 singles on the billboard hot 100 and won her a grammy award for best pop vocal album. her fourth album, "good girl gone bad" (2007), produced two top 10 singles on the billboard hot 100 and earned her a grammy award for best female pop vocal performance. her fifth album, "mechanical bull" (2009), produced one top 10 single on the billboard hot 100. presley has also appeared in several television series, including "the wonder years", "er", "dawson's creek", and " csi: crime scene
greenville creek is a tributary of the catawba river in western north carolina. it is approximately long and has a drainage area of . the creek rises in the pisgah national forest southeast of greenville and flows generally northwestwardly through the counties of transylvania, mitchell, and haywood before joining the catawba river about north of morganton. the creek has two major tributaries, the east fork and the west fork. the creek is a popular destination for fishing, kayaking, and canoeing. it provides drinking water to residents of the haywood county communities of waynesville and clyde. the creek has also been
arkady adamovich brish (may 14, 1917 – march 7, 1997) was a soviet mathematician and physicist. he made significant contributions to the theory of relativity and quantum field theory. born in kiev, ukraine, brish was a student at the kiev polytechnic institute when he was drafted into the red army during world war ii. after the war he returned to the kiev institute and became a leading figure in soviet physics. in 1964 he was awarded the stalin prize for his work on quantum field theory. he retired from the soviet academy of sciences in 1984 and died in moscow
dendropsophus phlebodes, the san carlos treefrog or red-eyed treefrog, is a species of frog in the family hylidae. it is endemic to the san carlos national forest in central-western costa rica. this species grows to a size of about and has a broad, flat head. it is typically green or olive green but may be red in color. the dorsal surface of its body may be lighter or darker than the ventral surface, and the tips of its fingers and toes are black. the front toes have a small web between them. this species is found in moist primary forests,
donald ogden stewart (november 30, 1894 - december 2, 1976) was an american writer and artist. he is best known for his novels and short stories, which often explore the themes of art, love, and tragedy. donald ogden stewart was born on november 30, 1894 in new york city. after graduating from high school in 1914, stewart studied at the art students league of new york under the guidance of robert henri. he served in world war i as a medical officer with the united states army medical corps, and afterwards began to write fiction. stewart's first published story, "the
love of life", appeared in the magazine the smart set in 1922. his first novel, the outsider (1926), was highly acclaimed and won the pulitzer prize. his subsequent novels include the great gatsby (1925), the sun also rises (1926), and to have and have not (1937). during world war ii, stewart served as an art critic for the united states army forces in europe. he later resumed writing fiction, publishing such novels as the return of sherlock holmes (1943) and the ghost writer (1947). in 1951 he was awarded the nobel prize in literature. stewart died on december 2, 1976
lemuel franklin smith (april 21, 1890 – july 11, 1972) was an american jurist and politician who served as the 36th governor of arkansas from 1944 to 1948. smith was born in atkins, arkansas, and attended public schools in his hometown. he graduated from the university of arkansas in 1913 and passed the bar in 1914. smith practiced law in atkins until 1916, when he entered the united states army as a private first class. he served in france during world war i and attained the rank of lieutenant colonel. after the war, smith resumed the practice of law in
atkins. in 1928, smith was elected to the arkansas house of representatives, where he served for two terms. in 1934, he was elected to the arkansas senate, where he served for six terms. in 1942, smith was elected governor of arkansas on a ticket with fellow democrat j. william fulbright. as governor, smith promoted economic development and public education. he also oversaw the construction of several major infrastructure projects in arkansas during his term, including a new state capitol building and a bridge over the arkansas river connecting arkadelphia to batesville. smith retired from office in 1948 after serving two
milan aleksić , nicknamed miša (миша), known professionally as miša aleksić-marinko (миша алексић-маринко, born 15 november 1984) is a montenegrin singer. he has won several music awards in his homeland, and has also achieved success in serbia, croatia, and slovenia. aleksić-marinko was born on 15 november 1984 in nikšić, montenegro. he started his musical career at the age of 10, when he began singing in a choir. he then took private singing lessons and joined a local pop group. in 2003, he represented montenegro in the eurovision song contest 2003 with the song "nije ljubav stvar" (english: "it's not love").
georges auguste escoffier (; 28 october 1846 – 24 november 1910) was a french chef and restaurateur who is considered the father of modern french cuisine. he is also credited with popularizing the use of wine in cooking, and his innovations in the field of kitchen management and cuisine have had a profound effect on the way that food is presented and consumed worldwide. escoffier was born in linz, then part of the austrian empire, into a family of wine merchants. after attending the lycée louis-le-grand in paris, he began his career as a chef in the kitchens of the
hôtel ritz. in 1875, he moved to the newly founded restaurant le grand véfour, where he became head chef. in 1878, he published "le guide culinaire", which became one of the most influential cookbooks of its time. he retired from le grand véfour in 1903, but continued to work as a consultant to various restaurants until his death. escoffier was a member of both the french academy of sciences and the royal society of arts. he received numerous awards and accolades throughout his career, including being named an officer of the legion of honour and a grand officer of the
heath hall (formerly east weald) is a grade ii* listed building in heath, west sussex, england. it is a large country house, constructed in the late 18th century for the gurney family. the present building is largely a georgian reconstruction, with some elements from the earlier elizabethan and jacobean periods. the house has been used as a girls' school since 1929. heath hall was built for the gurney family in about 1770. the architect is unknown, but it is thought to have been based on designs by inigo jones. it is a large country house, constructed in the late 18th
the illinois country ( ; , i.e. "the land of the illinois") was a region in the midwest united states that was first claimed by france, and then by the united states. the area encompassed parts of what are now the states of illinois, wisconsin, indiana, michigan and ohio. the illinois country was first claimed by france in 1673. in 1763, after the seven years' war, the british ceded the region to france as part of the treaty of paris. the french established a colony along the mississippi river called new france. the illinois country encompassed parts of what are
now the states of illinois, wisconsin, indiana, michigan and ohio. in 1803, following the war of 1812, the united states acquired most of new france, including the illinois country. the u.s. congress defined the territory as comprising all land east of the mississippi river and north of spanish florida, except for west florida (now louisiana). the u.s. government established fort dearborn near chicago in 1803 as its first permanent settlement in what would become the great lakes region. in 1816, congress passed a law incorporating all former french territory west of the mississippi into louisiana territory. this created a border
edwin regur sweetland (january 10, 1875 – february 4, 1950) was an american psychologist and educator who is considered one of the pioneers of behaviorism. he is also known for his contributions to the development of psychological measurement and for his work on animal behavior. edwin sweetland was born on january 10, 1875 in rochester, new york. after receiving his undergraduate degree from harvard university in 1898, sweetland attended the university of berlin for a year before returning to the united states to study under john b. watson at johns hopkins university. in 1902, sweetland received his doctorate from johns
hopkins, and he subsequently began teaching at the university of chicago. in 1916, sweetland relocated to the university of california, berkeley where he remained until his retirement in 1949. sweetland's major contribution to psychology was his development of behaviorism as a scientific theory. behaviorism is a school of thought that holds that all behaviors are governed by observable responses to stimuli. this approach made it possible to study behavior in a laboratory setting and to develop methods for measuring individual differences in behavior. sweetland also made important contributions to the development of psychological measurement, particularly through his work on psychometric
soil contamination, soil pollution, or land pollution is the contamination of the soil or ground water with hazardous or toxic substances. soil contamination can take many forms, including the introduction of pollutants from the air, water, or land surface. soil contamination can result from a variety of sources, including industrial activity, automobiles and trucks, agricultural activities (such as pesticide use), and natural phenomena (such as volcanic eruptions). soil contamination can also occur as a result of human activity, such as improper disposal of waste products or improper use of pesticides. soil pollution can have significant negative consequences for human health
a 3d content retrieval system is a machine learning algorithm used for the purpose of retrieving information from three-dimensional (3d) data. 3d content retrieval has been employed in a number of fields, such as computer vision, medical image retrieval, and 3d printing. a number of different machine learning algorithms have been used for this purpose, including support vector machines (svms), nearest neighbor algorithms, and bayesian networks. 3d content retrieval is often used in conjunction with 2d content retrieval, as the two algorithms can be used to retrieve different types of information from the same 3d data. for example, 2d content
