ludwig ferdinand huber or louis ferdinand huber (november 5, 1809 – october 24, 1892) was a german physician who was the father of bacteriologist robert huber. ludwig ferdinand huber was born in 1809 in the town of oberndorf am neckar, then part of the kingdom of württemberg. after completing his schooling at tübingen and heidelberg, he studied medicine at the university of tübingen. he received his doctorate in 1835 and became a doctor at the university of basel. huber's early work focused on physiological problems relating to anesthesia and surgery. in 1843 he published a paper that described the first
successful operation using gas anesthesia. in 1847 he was appointed professor of anatomy and physiology at the university of strasbourg. huber is most famous for his work on bacteria. in 1849 he published a paper titled "über bacterien" (on bacteria), which is considered to be one of the seminal works in the field of microbiology. in this paper, huber described bacteria as small organisms that could cause diseases in humans and other animals. his work led to the development of modern medical practices such as antiseptics and antibiotics. huber retired from teaching in 1875 and died two years later at
