calvin b. fowler (february 11, 1940 – january 30, 2006) was an american author, journalist, and professor. fowler was born in dallas, texas. he attended the university of texas at austin, where he received his b.a. in 1962. fowler then attended the university of california, berkeley, where he received his m.a. in 1964 and his ph.d. in 1968. fowler began his career as a journalist for the "dallas morning news" in 1966. he was also a senior writer for "time" magazine from 1971 to 1973, and a columnist for "the washington post" from 1978 to 1986. fowler was also a
negusie v. holder, 555 u.s. 511 (2009), was a case in the united states supreme court that addressed the constitutionality of section 5 of the voting rights act of 1965. the case was decided in a 7-2 decision, with the majority ruling that section 5 is constitutional. section 5 of the voting rights act of 1965 requires certain states and municipalities with a history of racial discrimination in voting to receive approval from the department of justice (doj) before making any changes to their voting laws. negusie v. holder concerned whether or not this requirement constitutes an unconstitutional burden on
