heteronormativity is the concept that heterosexuality is the only valid and normal orientation. this can include discrimination or hostility towards people who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, or any other non-heterosexual orientation. the term "heteronormativity" was first coined in the late 1970s by gay rights activist michel foucault. he used it to describe a pervasive cultural norm in which all heterosexual relationships are seen as normatively desirable and natural. this norm can produce discrimination or hostility towards people who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, or any other non-heterosexual orientation. heteronormativity has been critiqued for its exclusion of transgender
henry petroski (february 6, 1942) is an american engineer and theorist who has written on various aspects of engineering. he is particularly known for his work on the design and assessment of systems, his writing on the history and philosophy of engineering, and his books on the design process. henry petroski was born in 1942 in philadelphia, pennsylvania, united states. he obtained a b.s. in mathematics from princeton university in 1964 and an m.s. in civil engineering from the university of california, berkeley, in 1965. he became a professor at stanford university in 1969, where he remained until his retirement
