starodub-on-the-klyazma was a prominent urban centre in the medieval rus state. it was situated on the river klyazma, about 25 km south-east of the modern city of nizhny novgorod. the earliest mention of starodub dates to the 10th century, when it was known as staryi dub. in 1018, vladimir i of kiev founded a monastery on the site of an earlier pagan temple, and named it after his patron saint, the virgin mary. by the 12th century, starodub had become one of the most important urban centres in medieval rus, and it continued to grow in importance during the 13th
and 14th centuries. in 1237, starodub became the capital of a principality that was ruled by yuri dolgoruky. the principality grew powerful and prosperous, and by the 1350s it had become one of the most important states in medieval rus. in 1375, yuri ii of vladimir conquered starodub, and made it his capital. the principality lasted until 1401, when it was absorbed into the grand duchy of moscow. starodub continued to be a significant town even after it ceased to be a principality. it was home to a large number of merchants and craftsmen, and it remained an important trade
mountjoy square is a georgian garden square in dublin, ireland. the garden was laid out in 1683 by the earl of mountjoy, who also commissioned the nearby royal hospital for incurables. the square was designated a protected monument in 1926. mountjoy square is located on the north side of saint stephen's green, between parnell square and dawson street. it is bounded by dawson street to the east, mountjoy street to the south, and grafton street to the west. the square is dominated by the 17th century montjoy house, which now houses the irish museum of modern art. the surrounding gardens
